<font color="#FF0000">MAYA YING LIN'S DESIGN </font><br>
<tt>Thu Dec 12 17:15:51 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
What is remarkable about May Ying Lin's design of this public gathering place is they way it keeps before us as a nation these 57,661 U.S. veterns who were killed or missing in the Vietnam War. As a memorial, it says nothing about the controversial issues related to the war, the differences and conflicts of values and meanings that divided families and separated friends. As a memorial it does not take sides, neither glorifying nor profaning the war. Nor does it display the bravery and honor of the women and men who fought in it, or the courage of those who resisted. It simply shows the 57,661 friends, daughters, sons, fellow citizens who were killed or lost, regardless of whatever else we might think about the war. <br><br>
But it is precisely because of the simple visibility of these dead and lost veterns, presented as names on a wall without any ordering principle other than the chronological date of their dis-appearance, that anyone of us, whatever our background, values and belives, whether protestors or supportors of the war, whether we served in Vitenam or escaped the draft, is invited and welcomed into this space, to think about the conflict known as Vietnam and to begin to understand what is was (and still is) that divides and separates us from one another. In this space, created by Maya Ying Lin we can see each one of these 57,661 persons blended with the images of ourselves on the black polished surface of the wall, images affected and distorted by the names etched in the stone. Each of us, whatever our differences, is able to see the effects of power that resulted in the loss of 57,661 of our own citizens, whether we think we used that power correctly or not.<br><br>
What Maya Lin has given us is a public gathering place where each of us can revist the Vietnam War experience without being told what to think; where we, in all our diversity and differences, can see the same war dead and face the same consequences of our own actions, a space that keeps visible for us, no matter who we are, the 57,661 killed and missing. Perhaps, if we stand there long enought and re-visit it enought times, we can begin to find ways to live togehter with our social, cultural, philsophical and religious differences.
